  <entry>
    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w35429</id>
    <title>Benefit-Based Taxation can Include Substantial Redistribution</title>
    <updated>2026-07-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Jo Ellery &amp; Matthew C. Weinzierl</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;Contrary to a long-standing concern, we present evidence that classical benefit-based labor income taxation in the tradition of Smith (1776) is consistent with income redistribution through transfers and negative average tax rates both theoretically and---in plausibly-specified simulations---quantitatively at levels which reflect U.S. policy over the past several decades. As redistribution is widespread in practice, our results remove an obstacle to the benefit principle’s plausibility as a prevailing normative foundation of tax policy.</content>
    <link href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w35429"/>
    <category term="NBER"/>
    <published>2026-07-01T00:00:00+00:00</published>
